I need a way to compare the sizes of different power plants. There is information about the capacity, as well as the actual energy production. Counting the NaN values in both gives me an idea of which information to use.

In [3]:
data[['capacity_mw', 'generation_gwh_2019']].isna().value_counts()
Out[3]:
capacity_mw  generation_gwh_2019
False        True                   25277
             False                   9659
dtype: int64

Looks like all power plants have capacity data but only 9659 have information about actual electricity generation. That's why it makes sense to use the capacity to compare power plants.

I'll also compare the plants based on their primary fuel. First I'll answer these questions:

  • How many power plants use each primary fuel?
  • What is the total capacity (MW) of all primary fuels globally?
In [4]:
byFuel = data.groupby(data['primary_fuel']).agg({'primary_fuel':'count', 'capacity_mw':'sum'})
byFuel.rename(columns={'primary_fuel':'plants'}, inplace=True)
byFuel.sort_values('plants', ascending=True, inplace=True)
byFuel

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(11,8))
yAxis = np.arange(0, len(byFuel.index))
barHeight = 0.4

ax.barh(y=yAxis-barHeight/2, width=byFuel['plants'], height=barHeight, 
        color='indigo', label='Number of Plants', zorder=3, edgecolor='black')
ax.set_xlabel('Number of Plants')
ax.set_facecolor('#00BFFF11')

ax2 = ax.twiny()

ax2.barh(y=yAxis+barHeight/2, width=byFuel['capacity_mw'], height=barHeight, 
         color='goldenrod', label='Total Capacity', zorder=3, edgecolor='black')
ax2.set_xlabel('Total Capacity (MW)')

plt.yticks(yAxis, byFuel.index)

plt.title('Power Plants by Primary Fuel')

ax.legend(loc=(0.7,0.1))
ax2.legend(loc=(0.7,0.14))

ax.grid(axis='x', zorder=1, color='indigo', alpha=0.3)

plt.show()

Looking at the results, there are definitely some interesting trends to notice.

  • Solar, hydro and wind power are the most used forms of energy measured in the number of plants
  • However, solar and wind energy are only the 7th and 5th largest energy forms in combined energy capacity
  • The most efficient fuels (comparing the average power plant capacity) seem to be nuclear, coal and gas

Moving on, I'm adding another grouper, based on whether the primary fuel is renewable or not. I'll use it to calculate which countries have the capacity to produce the most renewable energy compared to non-renewable energy.

In [6]:
data['renewable'] = np.where(data['primary_fuel'].isin(['Geothermal', 'Hydro', 'Solar', 'Wave and Tidal', 'Wind']), 1, 0)
#data.loc[(data.primary_fuel == 'Other'), 'renewable'] = np.NaN
In [7]:
renew = data.groupby(['country_long', 'renewable']).agg(total_capacity=('capacity_mw', sum))
renew = renew.reset_index()

In [8]:
renew = renew.pivot(index='country_long', columns='renewable', values='total_capacity')
renew = renew.reset_index().rename_axis(None,axis='columns')
renew = renew.rename(columns={1.0:'renewable_mw', 0.0:'nonrenewable_mw'})
renew = renew.replace(np.NaN, 0)
renew['renewable_ratio'] = renew.renewable_mw / (renew.renewable_mw + renew.nonrenewable_mw)
renew.sort_values('renewable_ratio', ascending=False)

Last thing I want to do is to find out whether there's a correlation between any variables in my data. I'll convert text data through category type to category codes and call a correlation chart.

In [19]:
categoricalData = data[['country', 'latitude', 'longitude', 'primary_fuel', 'commissioning_year', 'capacity_mw', 'generation_gwh_2019']]

for col in categoricalData:
    if categoricalData[col].dtype == 'object':
        categoricalData[col] = categoricalData[col].astype('category')
        categoricalData[col] = categoricalData[col].cat.codes
In [20]:

Conclusions: neither country nor location correlates with any column. There's a strong correlation between capacity and generation (as expected), and also a weaker correlation between primary fuel and commissioning year (probably through renewable solutions becoming more and more common).
